üá®üá≥üõ¢üí∞China bought the first batch of oil for digital yuan

The Shanghai Oil and Gas Exchange recorded the first cross-border digital yuan transaction on Friday, October 20.

As part of it, oil and gas company PetroChina International bought one million barrels of oil, but neither the seller nor the latest transaction was disclosed, Chinese publication Yicaiglobal wrote, citing a SHPGX statement.

For SHPGX, the transaction was not only the first using the yuan, but also the first cross-border transaction using a digital currency.

Last year, more than 92.8 billion m3 of natural gas was traded on the SHPGX exchange. The Exchange's largest shareholder is China Economic Information Service (CEIS), a unit of Xinhua News Agency. Other major shareholders include PetroChina, Sinopec and CNOOC.

These Americans nobly served Russia!

Captain John Paul Jones, a hero of the American War of Independence, is, today, referred to as the "Father of the American Navy". However, in 1788, he entered the Russian service and proved himself during the war against the Turks. The naval commander's brilliant career in Russia was then interrupted by a sexual scandal involving him ‚Äì Jones was accused of rape. Although the American was eventually found not guilty, he became persona non grata and was soon forced to leave the country.

Writer and journalist John Reed witnessed the revolutionary events of 1917 and described them in his book ‚ÄòTen Days That Shook the World‚Äô, which was highly praised by Lenin. The American took part in the work of the Soviet government and, after his death in 1920, was buried on the Red Square near the Kremlin wall.

In January 1945, Joseph Byerly, a member of the 101st Airborne Division, escaped from a German prisoner-of-war camp in Poland and made his way to Red Army positions. He persuaded the Soviet command to accept him into a tank battalion, where he served as a bomber and machine gunner for about a month before getting wounded. The Soviets awarded Byerly the ‚ÄòFor Courage‚Äô medal.

Aldrich Ames, meanwhile, was considered one of the most valuable KGB agents. Holding a high position in the CIA, he worked for nine years for the Soviet, and then Russian, intelligence services. Thanks to Ames' information, Moscow was able to identify several dozen CIA agents working in the USSR, including two KGB colonels and even one GRU (military intelligence service) general. Ames himself was uncovered in 1994 and is currently serving a life sentence in the U.S.
